  <section id="pattern158-origin" class="content-section">
    <h2>Pattern 158</h2>
    <div class="origin-story">
      <p>Near the end of Myst, the brothers Sirrus and Achenar whisper a clue through their prison books: <em>&ldquo;The final page is in the fireplace... Pattern 158.&rdquo;</em></p>
      <p>You find the pattern book in the library, enter the code on the fireplace grid, and a wall rotates open to reveal a hidden chamber. It works. You've solved the puzzle.</p>
      <p>Except you haven't. The brothers are manipulating you. They want you to retrieve their final pages so they can escape. The obvious answer &mdash; the red and blue pages &mdash; is a trap. The real solution is the green book sitting right next to them. Their father Atrus is inside it. He knows what they did. And the entire puzzle was designed to stop you from seeing that.</p>
      <p><strong>Pattern 158 = the code that reveals both the trap and the true solution.</strong></p>
      <p>That's how I approach engineering problems. The obvious answer is often a trap. The real problem is usually sitting right next to the stated problem &mdash; you have to see through the framing to find it. Every forensic investigation I've run has had this shape: what the client reported and what was actually happening were related, but not the same thing.</p>
    </div>
